Perfect — this error is expected, and you’ve hit a very important Chrome-extension boundary. I’ll explain why it’s happening, how extensions are actually “installed”, how to add logs to see what’s working, and what you can realistically test right now.
I’ll also give counterpoints + wrong directions, as you asked.

1️⃣ Why you’re seeing

“Extension not installed or permission denied.”

✅ The real reason (no sugar-coating)

This line in your website:

JavaScript
chrome.runtime.sendMessage(EXTENSION_ID, ...)

❌ CANNOT WORK from a normal website unless ALL of the following are true:

The extension is installed

You are using the correct extension ID

The extension explicitly allows external messaging

You are testing in Chrome, not another browser

Right now, at least (2) and (3) are missing.

2️⃣ How Chrome extensions are actually “installed”
✅ Correct way to install your extension (dev mode)

Open Chrome

Go to:

chrome://extensions

Enable Developer mode (top-right)

Click Load unpacked

Select your extension/ folder
(the folder containing manifest.json)

After this:

Chrome assigns your extension an ID

Example:

abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz123456

📌 This ID is REQUIRED in your website code.

❌ Common wrong assumption

“If I have the files, the extension is installed”

❌ No.
Until you load it via chrome://extensions, Chrome does not know it exists.

3️⃣ REQUIRED CHANGE: allow website → extension messaging

Your extension must explicitly allow external websites to talk to it.

✅ Update manifest.json (MANDATORY)
JSON
{
  "manifest_version": 3,
  "name": "Chat Context Extractor",
  "version": "0.1",
  "permissions": ["tabs", "scripting"],
  "background": {
    "service_worker": "background.js"
  },
  "externally_connectable": {
    "matches": ["http://localhost/*", "http://127.0.0.1/*"]
  },
  "content_scripts": [
    {
      "matches": ["<all_urls>"],
      "js": ["content.js"],
      "run_at": "document_idle"
    }
  ]
}

⚠️ Counterpoint
Without externally_connectable, Chrome blocks all website messages silently.

4️⃣ Where to add console.log (VERY IMPORTANT)
🔹 A. content.js (page console, NOT extension console)

Add logs here:

JavaScript
