Good — this is a very common async bug in Chrome extensions, and your code is almost correct.
The “uncaught promise” error is happening because of how message passing works with async listeners.

Let’s fix it properly and explain both sides so you understand why.

🚨 Why you get “Uncaught (in promise)” here

The problem is NOT this line itself:

JavaScript
console.log("[BG] Scraped:", scrapeResult.messages.length);

The real issue happens before it:

JavaScript
const scrapeResult = await chrome.tabs.sendMessage(...)

If the content script:

fails

times out

doesn’t respond

or connection closes

then scrapeResult becomes undefined → promise rejects → uncaught error.

🧠 Chrome message system rule (IMPORTANT)

When using async listeners:

sendResponse() must remain valid

but an async listener automatically returns a Promise, which Chrome does NOT fully support.

This causes random:

Uncaught (in promise)

even when logic is correct.

✅ PROFESSIONAL FIX (used in real extensions)
❌ Don’t make listener async directly.

Instead:

keep listener NON-async

run async code inside an IIFE.

⭐ Replace your background.js listener with THIS
JavaScript
